## 📌 Real-World Reality

### Case: Wannacry Ransomware (2017)

```
Investigation after attack:

Timeline reconstruction:
├─ 2017-05-12 14:32:00 → Vulnerable Windows system infected via EternalBlue exploit
├─ 2017-05-12 14:35:00 → Ransomware payload executes, starts encryption
└─ 2017-05-12 15:00:00 → Company pays ransom (then starts investigation)

DFIR findings:
├─ Root cause: Unpatched Windows (MS17-010 patch available for 2 months!)
├─ Persistence: None found (ransomware didn't install backdoor)
├─ Lateral movement: Infected multiple systems on same network (poor segmentation)
├─ Impact: 200,000+ files encrypted across 5 servers

Lessons learned:
├─ Patch management is critical (this was preventable)
├─ Network segmentation needed (ransomware shouldn't cross boundaries)
└─ Backups are better than ransom (restore time 72 hours vs ransom + decryption uncertainty)
```

### Case: Insider Threat (Real SOC)

```
Scenario: Employee fired, suspected data theft

DFIR Timeline:
├─ 2024-01-10 → Employee notified of termination
├─ 2024-01-10 15:00:00 → Employee accesses "Confidential_Formulas" folder (unusual)
├─ 2024-01-10 16:30:00 → Large file upload to personal OneDrive (500MB)
├─ 2024-01-10 18:00:00 → Employee logs out, leaves office
└─ 2024-01-11 → Investigation begins

Forensic evidence:
├─ Browser history shows OneDrive login (personal account)
├─ File staging in %TEMP% (compression before upload)
├─ Deletion attempts (Shift+Delete, not recovery possible)
└─ Email to competitor (found in Outlook cache)

Conclusion:
✓ Confirmed insider threat
✓ Data exfiltrated to personal account (could be accessed from anywhere)
✓ Proof for legal action

Action:
├─ Legal: Lawsuit against employee
├─ Technical: Change credentials, audit cloud storage
└─ Process: Implement USB blocking, DLP (Data Loss Prevention) on cloud uploads
```

